An aerial view of the solar mirrors at the Noor 1 Concentrated Solar Power (CSP) plant, near the central Moroccan town of Ouarzazate. (AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Ouarzazate - Morocco's king is unveiling one of the world's biggest solar plants, taking advantage of the Sahara sunshine and a growing push for renewable energy.King Mohammed VI is scheduled to inaugurate the $3.9bn project on Thursday in the southern town of Ouarzazate.The plant, also known as Noor I, is the first phase of a project expected to provide 1.2 million Moroccans with power.The Climate Investment Funds, a major funder of the project, says it will be the world's biggest concentrated solar plant, meaning it that will store power to generate when the sun isn't shining.While it's aimed at reducing carbon emissions, environmental activists are concerned that it will require water from a nearby dam for cooling, at a time of ongoing drought.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.